{meta: title I Will Trade the Old Cross for a Crown}
{meta: artist Doyle Lawson}
{meta: composer Johnson Oatman Jr. and John M. Henson}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]I shall not bear the [D7]cross through yon [G]city
When the [C]burdens of life I lay [G]down
When I knock on the [D7]portals of [G]heaven
I will [C]trade the old [D7]cross for a [G]crown
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
Though the cross often [D7]times has been [G]heavy
And all [C]fortune on me begins to [G]frown
But how happy I'll [D7]be over [G]yonder
When I [C]trade the old [D7]cross for a [G]crown
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
And I will trade the old [D7]cross for a [G]crown
When the [D7]burdens of [A7]life I lay [D7]down
When those [G]pearly gates for [B7]me shall swing [C]open
[G]I will [C]trade the old [D7]cross for a [G]crown
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Every cross that I [D7]bear for my [G]Savior
Will at [C]last one day when He calls me lay [G]down
And all my sorrow will [D7]then be for[G]gotten
And that's when I'll [C]trade the old [D7]cross for a [G]crown
{end_of_verse}

